2carboxyl) and C2 (alcohol\u2192ketone), which is hard to achieve with non-specific photocatalysis. UV/TiO\u2082 would likely over-oxidize or fragment the substrate.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Consider a stepwise oxidation: glyceraldehyde \u2192 glyceric acid \u2192 3-hydroxypyruvate\", \"Use MnO\u2082 or Fe(III) as milder, more selective oxidants\", \"Cite Kua & Bada 2011 or similar for selective prebiotic oxidation\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.70,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.75,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n      \"feedback\": \"Longest pathway variant combining the weaknesses of both formate reduction (rxn_003) and the non-selective photocatalytic oxidation (rxn_008). While individual steps are plausible, the accumulated yield losses over 6 steps are concerning for prebiotic plausibility.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"This pathway has too many sequential bottlenecks; consider pruning\", \"The P10 glyoxylate route achieves the same endpoint more efficiently\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.76,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.76,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n      \"feedback\": \"Similar issues to P4 with the rxn_008 oxidation step being problematic. The direct glycolaldehyde entry (rxn_015) shortens the pathway but doesn't address the selectivity issue in the oxidation step.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Replace rxn_008 with a two-step selective oxidation sequence\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.76,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.72\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.74,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.75,\n      \"feedback\": \"Elegant metabolic analog using transamination, but the longest pathway with 7 steps. Combines the problematic rxn_008 with non-enzymatic transamination (rxn_012) which, while demonstrated with pyridoxal analogs, has low yields prebiotically. The pyruvate/alanine shuttle is a nice conceptual touch linking to modern metabolism.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Cite Zaborniakova et al. or Metzler et al. for prebiotic transamination evidence\", \"Consider keto acid + amine condensation with Cu\u00b2\u207a catalysis as alternative\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.77,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.74\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"Bucherer-Bergs route is a well-known alternative to Strecker for amino acid synthesis. The hydantoin intermediate (rxn_013) provides a stable protected form of the amino acid. Hydrolysis (rxn_014) typically needs elevated pH and temperature, which is plausible at alkaline vents. The input list for rxn_013 (glycolaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 + CO\u2082) correctly represents the Bucherer-Bergs mechanism.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify pH and temperature conditions for hydantoin hydrolysis\", \"Consider that hydantoin hydrolysis can proceed abiotically at pH > 9 and T > 80\u00b0C\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.76,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.77,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.74\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.77,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n      \"feedback\": \"Compact Bucherer-Bergs variant via FTT formaldehyde. Avoids the problematic formate reduction step. Good alternative pathway that provides chemical diversity in intermediate protection (hydantoin vs. aminonitrile). The 4-step length is efficient.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Strengthen rxn_014 by specifying alkaline conditions (pH 10-12) for hydrolysis\", \"Note that hydantoin intermediates are more stable than aminonitriles, providing temporal buffering\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.84,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway elegantly invokes the Eschenmoser glyoxylate scenario. The glyoxylic acid + form